Hon. J. A. MacKinnon (Minister of Mines and Resources): Mr. Speaker, it is much too early to make any worth-while statement as to the progress being made. The Department of Mines and Resources is in communication with the ministers of highways in the various provinces as to the route of the highway through their particular provinces, and the kind of road to be constructed. I think that is as far as the statement went that I made yesterday to a delegation from Sault Ste. Marie. They were speaking to me principally on the matter of the route through that part of the province of Ontario. No agreements have yet been arrived at between the federal government and any of the provinces, although negotiations are actively under way.

Mr. J. G. Diefenbaker (Lake Centre): I wish to ask a question supplementary to the one asked by the member for Vancouver South. Has any determination been made whether the route of the trans-Canada highway shall be by way of the Kicking Horse pass or the Yellowhead pass?

Mr. MacKinnon: No.

Mr. Cruickshank: Where are your provin- cial rights now?

Mr. Diefenbaker: I would ask the minister if it is intended to rely on the recommenda- tions of the provinces.

Mr. MacKinnon: I would say it is.

QUESTION AS TO PROGRESS TOWARD CANADA’S SELF-SUFFICIENCY

On the orders of the day:

Mr. J. H. Blackmore (Lethbridge): I desire to direct a question to the Minister of Trade and Commerce. Will the minister make a statement to the house some time soon giving an account of the progress the government has made since January 1, 1946 toward mak- ing Canada more self—sufﬁcient? Will he deal in some detail with the progress that was made in 1948, and that is being made in 1949?

Right Hon. C. D. Howe (Minister of Trade and Commerce): The question seems to sug- gest a very comprehensive study involving considerable research. I shall be glad to examine it. I think certain data bearing on the subject matter were tabled a few days

On the orders of the day:

Mr. Stanley Knowles (Winnipeg North Centre): I should like to direct a question to the Minister of National Health and Welfare. Can the minister tell the house when the gov- ernment intends to implement plank No. 11 in the new Liberal party platform?

On the basis of a telegram received from the Van- couver district council of the Canadian Legion, I wish to repeat that question today.
